(40, 15, 11, 41, 7, 15, 15, 'that which cometh out of the mouth', 'Defilement and Speech', 'Both passages emphasize that it is not what enters the mouth that defiles a person, but rather what comes out of it. This connection highlights a consistent teaching on the nature of defilement in relation to speech and actions.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 40, 15, 18, 20, 'that which cometh out of the mouth', 'Defilement and the Heart', 'Both passages emphasize that defilement comes from what comes out of the mouth, linking it to the heart''s intentions. This connection highlights the distinction between external actions and internal moral state.', 'theme', 0.517, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 59, 3, 5, 8, 'that which cometh out of the mouth', 'Defilement of the Tongue', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of defilement stemming from speech rather than food. Matthew highlights that what comes out of the mouth defiles a man, while James elaborates on the tongue''s destructive power and its ability to defile the whole body.', 'theme', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 40, 12, 34, 37, 'that which cometh out of the mouth', 'Connection of Speech and Heart', 'Both passages emphasize the significance of what comes out of the mouth as a reflection of one''s inner state. Matthew 15:11 states that defilement comes from what comes out, while Matthew 12:34-37 elaborates on how the mouth speaks from the abundance of the heart.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 54, 4, 4, 5, 'that which cometh out of the mouth', 'Defilement and Purity in Food', 'Both passages emphasize the idea that what comes from within a person, rather than external food, determines purity. Matthew highlights that defilement is about what comes out of the mouth, while 1 Timothy asserts that all food is good if received with thanksgiving.', 'theme', 0.426, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 42, 11, 38, 41, 'this defileth a man', 'Defilement and Inner Purity', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of inner purity over external rituals. Matthew highlights that what comes out of the mouth defiles a man, while Luke critiques the Pharisees for focusing on outward cleanliness instead of inward wickedness.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 11, 44, 10, 14, 15, 'this defileth a man', 'Defilement and Cleansing Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of what defiles a person. Matthew highlights that it is not what enters the mouth, while Acts discusses what God has cleansed, suggesting a shift in understanding of purity.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 11, 22, 13, 14, NULL, 'Response to Offense and Truth', 'This connection highlights the theme of speaking truth despite potential offense. In both passages, individuals confront authority with messages that may not align with popular opinion, emphasizing fidelity to divine instruction.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 46, 10, 32, 33, 'offended, after they heard this saying', 'Offense and Consideration for Others', 'This connection highlights the theme of avoiding offense to others. Both passages emphasize the importance of being mindful of how one''s words and actions affect different groups, whether the Pharisees or broader communities.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 40, 17, 27, 27, NULL, 'Concern for Offending Others', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of avoiding offense to others. In Matthew 15:12, the disciples note that the Pharisees were offended, while in Matthew 17:27, Jesus instructs to avoid offending them by providing a temple tax.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 47, 6, 3, 3, 'offended', 'Offense and Ministry Integrity', 'This connection highlights the theme of offense in relation to ministry. Both passages address the importance of avoiding offense to maintain the integrity of the ministry.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 48, 2, 5, 5, 'the Pharisees were offended', 'Offense and Truth in the Gospel', 'This connection highlights the theme of offense taken by religious leaders when confronted with the truth. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining the truth of the gospel despite opposition.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 12, 59, 3, 17, 17, 'the Pharisees were offended', 'Wisdom and Offense', 'This connection highlights the contrast between the offense taken by the Pharisees and the qualities of wisdom described in James. While the Pharisees were offended, true wisdom is characterized as peaceable and gentle, suggesting a divergence from their reaction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 43, 15, 2, 2, 'Every plant, which my heavenly Father hath not planted', 'Connection of Fruitfulness and Removal', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment on unfruitful entities. Both passages emphasize the removal of what is not planted or bearing fruit.', 'theme', 0.5589999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 23, 60, 21, 21, 'my heavenly Father hath not planted', 'Planting and Righteousness Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine planting, where Matthew speaks of plants not planted by the Father being uprooted, while Isaiah refers to the people as ''the branch of my planting.'' Both passages emphasize the significance of what God establishes and the righteousness of His people.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 23, 61, 3, 3, 'planted', 'Planting and Righteousness Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of planting by the Lord. Matthew speaks of plants not planted by the Father being uprooted, while Isaiah refers to those planted by the Lord as trees of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 19, 92, 13, 13, 'planted', 'Connection of Planting and Flourishing', 'This connection highlights the theme of being ''planted'' in relation to spiritual growth. Both passages emphasize the importance of divine planting for flourishing and vitality.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 40, 13, 40, 41, 'Every plant, which my heavenly Father hath not planted', 'Judgment of the Unplanted', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment on those not established by God. Both passages emphasize the removal of what is not planted by the Father, indicating a future reckoning for iniquity.', 'theme', 0.412, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 13, 46, 3, 12, 15, 'Every plant, which my heavenly Father hath not planted', 'Judgment of Works and Growth', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment on what is built or planted. Both passages emphasize that only what is established by God will endure, while that which is not will be removed or burned.', 'theme', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 42, 6, 39, 39, 'blind leaders of the blind', 'Blind Leaders and Their Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the danger of the blind leading the blind, suggesting that such guidance will lead to failure. The repeated phrase ''blind lead the blind'' underscores this theme of misguided leadership.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 23, 56, 10, 10, 'blind leaders of the blind', 'Blind Leaders and Watchmen', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of blindness among leaders. Matthew refers to ''blind leaders of the blind,'' while Isaiah describes ''His watchmen are blind.'' This connection highlights the failure of those meant to guide.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 40, 23, 16, 24, NULL, 'Blind Guides and Their Consequences', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''blind guides'' leading others astray, resulting in dire consequences. The metaphor of blindness illustrates the failure of the leaders to recognize spiritual truths, leading to their downfall.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 23, 9, 16, 16, 'blind leaders of the blind', 'Blind Leaders and Their Followers', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of misguided leadership. Matthew warns that blind leaders will lead their followers to destruction, paralleling Isaiah''s assertion that leaders cause the people to err and be destroyed.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 39, 2, 8, 8, 'blind leaders of the blind', 'Blind Leaders and Causing Stumble', 'Both passages emphasize the consequences of leading others astray. Matthew speaks of ''blind leaders of the blind,'' while Malachi addresses those who ''have caused many to stumble.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 15, 14, 24, 5, 31, 31, 'blind leaders of the blind', 'Blind Leaders and False Prophets', 'This connection highlights the theme of misguided leadership. Both passages emphasize the consequences of following blind leaders and false prophets, leading to downfall.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
